    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 6,
        "Tafseer": "\"He created you from one soul. Then He made from it its mate, and He sent down for you of the cattle eight mates. He creates you in the wombs of your mothers, creation after creation, within three darknesses. That is Allah, your Lord; to Him belongs sovereignty. There is no deity except Him, so how are you averted?\" (6)\n\nAllah Almighty Alone is the Creator and Provider, so He Alone is the Lord\n\nThis is a further explanation of the preceding verse—showing that since God alone is the Creator and He alone has arranged for sustenance, and you also accept these self-evident realities, where has your intellect been turned upside down that you associate others in His sovereignty!\n\n'He created you from one soul. Then He made from it its mate'—meaning God alone created you all from a single soul (Adam), then ran his progeny from a sperm-drop, and then made you into pairs. The meaning is: since the entire house was built and populated by God, and this is a reality which even you do not deny, where is the room for other deities besides God!\n\n'and He sent down for you of the cattle eight mates'—meaning the God Who created you also arranged for your sustenance. It is not that He created you and then entrusted the responsibility of your sustenance to others. These various kinds of cattle upon which your livelihood and sustenance depend are created by God alone; no one else has created them.\n\nHere, for the cattle, the words 'He sent down for you' (anzala lakum) are used in the same manner as the words 'We sent down iron' (anzalna al-hadid) have occurred. This style of expression is used in the Qur'an for various things, and its objective is to draw people's attention to the primary source of everything—showing that the One Who sends down everything is, in reality, Allah Almighty alone. He sent down the cattle, meaning He created them and spread them in the earth to fulfill human needs. This very perspective of reality stirs up the true feeling of gratitude within man; otherwise, man's eye remains stuck with the immediate causes of every blessing, and he forgets his true Sustainer.\n\n'eight mates': The word 'zawj' (mate) is used for a pair and also for an individual of a pair; here, it is used in this second sense. Among the domestic cattle, four were well-known in Arabia: sheep, goat, camel, and cow. The word 'An'am' is used for them. If we count both male and female of them, they make eight. Since the livelihood of the Arabs depended mostly upon them, Allah Almighty specifically referred to them to remind of His lordship. If the detailed explanation of this is required, have a look at what we wrote under verses 142–144 of Surah Al-An'am.\n\n'He creates you in the wombs of your mothers, creation after creation, within three darknesses'—after reminding of creation and lordship, this draws attention to His power, His craftsmanship, and His all-encompassing knowledge: that same God creates you in the wombs of your mothers, within three layers of darkness, traversing through different stages of creation. The details of these different stages are described in Surah Al-Mu'minoon as follows:\n\n'Then We made the sperm-drop into a clinging clot, and We made the clot into a lump [of flesh], and We made [from] the lump, bones, and We covered the bones with flesh; then We developed him into another creation.' (Al-Mu'minoon: 14).\n\nThe three layers of darkness point to the layers of the placenta, the womb, and the belly. The meaning is that the hand of the divine craftsman does not perform this craftsmanship in the light of the sun or electricity, but within three layers of veils. This is a testimony to the fact that His knowledge encompasses every manifest and hidden thing.\n\n'That is Allah, your Lord; to Him belongs sovereignty...'—meaning that same God Who has bestowed these blessings upon you is your Master and Owner. Everything is His property, and His is the sovereignty of the heavens and the earth; there is no deity besides Him, so how is your intellect turned upside down that you are turned away from the straight path to a completely wrong direction! 'Tusrafoon' (you are averted), the passive voice, points to the reality that after these clear signs of nature, there was no room to wander in any wrong direction, but you have handed over your reins to some devil who is making you wander in the valleys of deviation."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 7,
        "Tafseer": "\"If you disbelieve - indeed, Allah is Free of need of you. And He does not approve for His servants disbelief. And if you are grateful, He approves it for you; and no bearer of burdens will bear the burden of another. Then to your Lord is your return, and He will inform you of what you used to do. Indeed, He is Knowing of that within the breasts.\" (7)\n\nAllah Almighty is Entirely Free of Need of People's Disbelief and Faith\n\nThe word 'kufr' here is used in the sense of ungratefulness and ingratitude. In contrast to it is 'in tashkuroo' (if you are grateful), which clarifies this meaning. The meaning is: since no one else has any share in your creation and sustenance, if despite this, you are showing ungratefulness by making others partners of God, remember that you are not harming God in the least. God is free of need of your disbelief and your gratitude. He is not in need of you; rather, you are in need of Him. If you remain grateful to Him, He will approve it for you. Your blessings will be blessed in the world, and you will receive its full reward in the Hereafter. And if you show ungratefulness, remember that God does not approve ungratefulness from His servants; therefore, its result will necessarily appear before them.\n\n'and no bearer of burdens will bear the burden of another...'—and remember also that with God, the responsibility of every soul lies upon itself alone. No one else will answer for it. If you have assumed that your deities will advocate and intercede for you to save you from God's grasp, this false hope is not going to be realized. The return of everyone must be to God alone. No one else will be a protector or place of return. Allah Almighty will place the complete register of deeds before everyone. He is fully aware of the secrets of hearts as well. Neither does He need to ask anyone regarding anyone, nor will anyone dare to say before Him that there are some matters regarding someone which are not in the knowledge of God."
