    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 8,
        "Tafseer": "\"And when adversity touches man, he calls upon his Lord, turning to Him; then when He bestows on him a favor from Himself, he forgets Him whom he called upon before, and he attributes to Allah equals to mislead [people] from His way. Say, 'Enjoy your disbelief for a little; indeed, you are of the companions of the Fire.'\" (8)\n\nWonder and Regret over Man's Ungratefulness\n\nThis is an expression of wonder and regret over this ungratefulness of man—showing that he has a strange condition: when some adversity touches him, he calls upon God with great humility and devotion, but when Allah Almighty removes his adversity to bless him with His favor, he forgets his adversity and begins to attribute God's favor to other partners, and in this way, turns away from the path of God himself and also turns others away from it. Since the attitude of the leaders of disbelief is discussed here, the active verb 'liyudilla' (to mislead) is used—meaning they mislead people. The meaning of being misled themselves is automatically included within this.\n\nThis same theme is expressed below in this very Surah as follows:\n\n'And when adversity touches man, he calls upon Us; then when We bestow on him a favor from Us, he says, \"I was only given it because of knowledge.\"' (49).\n\nThere is no consciousness of any deity besides the One God within human nature; because of this, when some state of real need overcomes him, he turns to Him alone and supplicates to Him. But when his adversity is removed, he forgets the adversity and also becomes indifferent to God, and attributes God's favor either to his assumed deities or declares it as the result of his own planning, capability, and intelligence, and thus becomes a partner of God himself.\n\n'Say, \"Enjoy your disbelief for a little; indeed, you are of the companions of the Fire.\"' Although the preceding statement was made in a general form, the objective was to draw attention to the state of the addressees; because of this, the Prophet (pbuh) was instructed to tell them: 'Enjoy life for a few days despite this ungratefulness and disbelief of yours; ultimately, you are going to become the fuel of Hell, which will fully settle all accounts.'"
