    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 9,
        "Tafseer": "\"Is he who is devoutly obedient during periods of the night, prostrating and standing [in prayer], fearing the Hereafter and hoping for the mercy of his Lord, [like one who does not]? Say, 'Are those who know equal to those who do not know?' Only they will remember who are people of understanding.\" (9)\n\nA Style of the Arabic Language\n\nIt has been clarified in various places in this book that in such interrogative sentences, a part of the discourse is omitted, which is obvious from the force of the speaker's expression. Below in verse 22, an example of this is also coming. This style is proof of the speaker's intensity of certainty, and from it, it also emerges that there is no room for difference for the addressee in the answer to this question. Furthermore, a part of the statement is expressed without being uttered: 'Is he who is devoutly obedient during periods of the night, prostrating and standing [in prayer] before his Lord, fearing the Hereafter and hoping for the mercy of his Lord, like one who is caught in arrogance and disbelief? Both are equal?'\n\nThe Belief of False Intercession Makes Good and Evil Equal\n\nFrom this question, it emerged automatically that these two cannot be equal in the sight of God, and this is such a self-evident reality that there was no room for denial even for the addressee; but despite this, foolish people had made good and evil entirely equal by inventing the belief of polytheism and intercession. This is because when salvation depended on the intercession of deities instead of faith and righteous deeds, neither did any fear of God's justice remain, nor any need for faith and righteous deeds.\n\nHaving understood the style of the verse and its context, now look at its individual parts.\n\n'Qunoot' primarily means humility, lowliness, and devotion before Allah. This is a state of the heart, the best expression of which is in prayer, particularly in night prayers. The restriction of 'periods of the night' (ana'al-layl) is placed specifically because the night prayer is free from any trace of show; therefore, the devotion of those who perform it is beyond doubt.\n\n'prostrating and standing' (sajidan wa qa'iman) is a depiction of their prayer—showing that they are sometimes in prostration, sometimes in standing. This expresses their restlessness—that while others are sleeping in their soft beds, they are in prostration and standing in search of their Lord's pleasure.\n\n'fearing the Hereafter and hoping for the mercy of his Lord' describes the inner state of their prayer—showing that the fear of the Hereafter and the hope of His mercy have produced this restlessness within them, because of which they separate themselves from their beds to be sometimes in prostration, sometimes in standing.\n\nThe Condition for the Balance of a Servant's Relation with God\n\nIt should be kept in mind here that a servant's relation with God remains balanced only as long as it remains between fear and hope. If either of these dominates, the balance is lost. If hope dominates, man becomes indifferent to God's justice, because of which he opens the doors of absolute license for himself. If fear dominates, despair and hopelessness find a way within him, and this too creates fitnah. The details of the corruptions that appeared in previous religions due to this lack of balance are very long. The Qur'an has pointed to them, and we have been drawing attention to them.\n\nThe True People of Knowledge in the Sight of the Qur'an\n\n'Say, \"Are those who know equal to those who do not know?\"' This sheds light on the omitted clause to which we pointed above—implying: how is it possible that the people of knowledge and those who do not know become equal in the sight of Allah? From this, it emerged automatically that in the sight of the Qur'an, the people of knowledge are those whose definition is stated with the words: 'Is he who is devoutly obedient during periods of the night, prostrating and standing...'. Those who do not possess this attribute are devoid of knowledge in the sight of the Qur'an, even if they travel to the moon and Mars. This is because for the guidance of life, the primary knowledge is that a person knows where this world came from, where it will end, what are the attributes of its Creator, and what is the nature of man's relation with Him. If the key of this knowledge has come into his hand, he will understand the purpose and end of his life, and if this knowledge is not achieved, he is in darkness, even if he measures the length and width of the heavens and the earth.\n\n'Only they will remember who are people of understanding'—meaning these realities are indeed obvious, but to accept them, it is not sufficient that they are obvious; it is also necessary that the addressees possess intellect and also utilize their intellect to hear and understand these realities. Those who possess neither knowledge nor intellect do not take any lesson from even the most obvious thing. In this, the Prophet (pbuh) is also consoled—stating that if these people are not benefiting from these reminders of the Qur'an, the fault lies neither in you nor in the Qur'an, but these people themselves are entirely dull and foolish."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 10,
        "Tafseer": "\"Say, 'O My servants who have believed, fear your Lord. For those who do good in this world is good, and the earth of Allah is spacious. Indeed, the patient will be given their reward without account.'\" (10)\n\nA Message of Consolation for the Oppressed Muslims\n\nAfter expressing despair over the attitude of the Quraysh, this is said to console those poor Muslims who were being persecuted at the hands of the Quraysh. The Prophet (pbuh) was instructed to deliver this word to My servants: 'Fear your Lord.' That is: foolish people have made the ways of polytheism and intercession to make God's justice and His reward and punishment entirely meaningless, but you continue to fear your Lord's justice. For those who lead a life of goodness in this world, there is a good reward with God. Those who are living in a fool's paradise relying on false intercessions will see the end of their foolishness.\n\n'and the earth of Allah is spacious'—meaning bear with resolve and courage the trials and afflictions which are being presented or will be presented by your enemies in this path. Even if you see that the land of your homeland has been made narrow for you, do not lose heart or despair; the earth of God is highly spacious. If it is made impossible for you to remain upon the religion of Allah in the city, Allah will guide you to some other land where you can worship your Lord without any fear.\n\nFrom this verse, it emerges that this Surah was revealed in that period of the conflict of truth and falsehood when the land of Makkah was becoming narrow for the Muslims and they were beginning to think about their future. At that time, Allah Almighty assured them that if the inhabitants of this city turn you out, rest assured that some other land will welcome you. Exactly this same theme, with this very context, has passed in Surah Al-Ankabut in these words:\n\n'O My servants who have believed, indeed My earth is spacious, so worship Me [alone].' (56).\n\n'Indeed, the patient will be given their reward without account'—meaning this is the path of highly severe trials, but rest assured that My servants who remain steadfast in these trials will receive their reward far beyond their expectations, estimations, and calculations. Today they cannot even conceive of it."
