        "AyahNumber": 11,
        "Tafseer": "\"Say, 'Indeed, I have been commanded to worship Allah, [being] sincere to Him in religion. And I have been commanded to be the first of the Muslims.'\" (11-12)\n\nDeclaration of Disassociation from the Opponents\n\nAfter blessing the Muslims with glad tidings, this is a declaration of self-sufficiency and disassociation from the opponents. The Prophet (pbuh) was instructed: 'Now there is no need to flatter them. Inform them clearly: \"I have been commanded to worship Allah, being sincere to Him in obedience, and I have also been commanded to be the first to submit (Muslim), regardless of what attitude others adopt.\"' This command has been given to the Prophet (pbuh) in various places, rather from the very first day of prophethood he had received this command. At the beginning of this Surah as well, this is mentioned in highly clear words: 'Indeed, We have revealed to you the Book in truth, so worship Allah, [being] sincere to Him in religion. Unquestionably, for Allah is the pure religion.' (2-3). Here, in both verses, two commands are mentioned. First, worshipping Allah alone, and second, becoming the first Muslim—meaning both faith and Islam have been commanded to me, and I have been instructed to be the first to submit. For this reason, I have put the collar of my Lord's obedience on my neck. Now, whoever wants to may join me, or else see their end. It should be clear that the very requirement of the office of a prophet is that he is the first to accept the faith and Islam to which he invites the creation; for this reason, his status is of the first of the believers (Awwal-ul-Mu'mineen) and the first of the Muslims (Awwal-ul-Muslimeen)."
