    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 14,
        "Tafseer": "\"Say, 'Allah [alone] I worship, sincere to Him in my religion. So worship what you will besides Him.' Say, 'Indeed, the losers are the ones who will lose themselves and their families on the Day of Resurrection. Unquestionably, that is the clear loss.'\" (14-15)\n\nDeclaration of Disassociation\n\nThis is a declaration of disassociation and self-sufficiency through the tongue of the Prophet (pbuh) in highly clear words—implying: 'In accordance with the command I have received from my Lord, I worship my Lord alone, being sincere to Him in obedience, and I invite you to this very thing. If you do not accept my word, worship whatever you will besides Him. I am free from this action of yours.' It states: 'Inform them of the reality as well: in reality, the losers are those who lose themselves and their families on the Day of Resurrection.' The meaning is: all other losses are temporary, and their compensation is possible, but the loss of the Day of Resurrection is eternal and everlasting; for this reason, unfortunate are those who are ruining their own and their families' Hereafter behind the temporary comfort of this world.\n\nEvery Person carries the Responsibility of Their Family\n\nWith 'themselves' (anfusahum), the addition of 'their families' (ahlihim) points to the reality that every person carries the responsibility of their family members along with the responsibility of their own soul. In the Hadith: 'Every one of you is a shepherd, and every one of you will be questioned regarding his flock,' the Prophet (pbuh) has clarified this reality. The requirement of this responsibility is that every person thinks of the salvation of their family along with their own salvation. If a person, by their wrong conduct, left a wrong example for their family, or by their power and influence, led them into a wrong path, they did not prepare only their own destruction, but also led them into an eternal ruin.\n\nActual Loss is the Loss of the Hereafter\n\n'Unquestionably, that is the clear loss'—meaning open your ears and hear well that the clear loss is that which will be faced in the Hereafter. The meaning is: today you are running away from this invitation of truth thinking that after accepting it you will have to sacrifice many worldly interests. However, this is no loss; the actual loss is that whose result is eternal deprivation.\n\nCredible Worship is That Accompanied by Sincere Obedience\n\nIn 'sincere to Him in my religion' (mukhlisan lahu deeni), the reality has been explained that with Allah, acceptable worship is only that which is accompanied by His pure obedience. If worship is performed to Allah, but obedience is performed to others contrary to His commands, this worship holds no value with Allah. Similarly, sincerity in obedience is also necessary. If Allah's obedience is performed merely for show, display, or some worldly interest, this hypocritical obedience also holds no value with Allah.\n\nHere, a point regarding the recitation is also worth mentioning. That is, the word 'Deen' should be recited with the dropping of the final 'ya' (deeni), just as is done in 'Lakum deenukum wa liya deen' (6), because it is established that the Prophet (pbuh) stopped on the verses. Sibawayh's view that this kind of dropping is specific to poetry is, in our view, incorrect. There are several examples of this kind of dropping in the Qur'an."
