        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 19,
        "Tafseer": "\"Then, is one who has deserved the decree of punishment [to be guided]? Are you, [O Muhammad], to save one who is in the Fire?\" (19)\n\nThe Mention of Those Who Have Deserved the Decree of Punishment\n\nThis consoled the Prophet (pbuh)—stating that those who receive God's guidance are those whose attributes have been described above. As for those who have deserved the decree of punishment, they are like those who are already in the Fire; so do you want to save those from Hell who are caught in the punishment? 'The decree of punishment' (Kalimat-al-Adhab) refers to that decisive decree of Allah which He uttered in reply to Iblis's challenge—stating: 'I will surely fill Hell with those who follow you, whether they be of the jinn or of men.' The meaning is: this decisive decree has been issued and is entirely inevitable; so those who have deserved it are indeed destined for Hell, who can save them!"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 20,
        "Tafseer": "\"But those who have feared their Lord - for them are chambers, above them chambers built, beneath which rivers flow. [This is] the promise of Allah. Allah does not fail in [His] promise.\" (20)\n\n'Lakin' (But) here is to introduce a contrast; therefore, its suitable translation is 'However/But'.\n\n'Mabniyyah' (built) here is in the sense of 'furnished' and 'decorated'. In Arabic, 'bana ad-dar' is used in the sense of constructing a house, and also in the sense of decorating it. Commentators have not paid attention to this meaning, but proofs of it exist in the Qur'an and Arabic usage.\n\n'the promise of Allah' is in the accusative case (mansoob) due to an omitted verb, and is for its emphasis.\n\nIn contrast to the punishment of the disbelievers which was described with the words: 'They will have canopies of fire above them and below them, canopies,' this describes the reward of those who feared their Lord and avoided polytheism. It states: for them will be decorated chambers, and above those chambers will be other decorated chambers. Beneath these chambers, rivers will be flowing. This is the firm promise of Allah, and Allah never violates His promise."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 21,
        "Tafseer": "4. Subsequent Theme: Verses 21–35\n\nNext, the cause of turning away of those who turn away from the Qur'an is struck—showing that the love of this transient world has hardened their hearts, because of which they are averse to the truth; whereas the Qur'an is a great blessing, and those who possess capability feel a shudder on hearing its verses. However, those whose hearts have become like stone will remain deprived of it, and will face the punishment which destroyed previous nations who denied the messengers. This Qur'an has explained all realities in the best of styles. Those who are opposing it are only preparing their own ruin. Blessed are those who accept this truth. They are the ones who fear Allah, and for them is the best reward... Recite the verses.\n\n5. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\nAyah 21\n\nA Reminder to the Deniers of the Qur'an\n\nThis is a reminder to the deniers of the Qur'an—showing that today you are being warned of the end, but you find it highly improbable; in the intoxication of your present successes, you do not understand from where the decline of your authority can appear, whereas you continuously observe that everything in this world is temporary and transient. Rain falls, with which springs of water flow in the earth, then various kinds and colors of crops and fields grow from it. Then they begin to dry up, then they turn yellow, then Allah Almighty turns them into scattered chaff. The word 'alwan' (colors) is used in the sense of varieties and kinds; its analysis has passed in its proper place.\n\n'He makes it dry' (yuhayyi-juhu) means its green begins to dry up.\n\n'Indeed in that is a reminder for those of understanding': That is, for those who utilize their intellect, there is a great lesson in this observation.\n\nWithin this, the greatest reminder is of the reality that all the pageantry and glory of this world are entirely temporary and transient; therefore, instead of being infatuated with them, the wise should turn to that Being Who is the Creator of all these things and is Self-Sustaining.\n\nThe second reminder in this is that the Sustainer Who has made this arrangement for His servants in this world, His lordship naturally requires that the servants show gratitude to Him alone, and do not associate anyone else in this gratitude.\n\nThe third is that the God Who made this arrangement of lordship, and Who subjected everything from the heaven to the earth to the service of man, will not leave people without purpose; rather, a Day is necessarily to come in which He will reckon every person for their good and bad deeds, and will reward or punish them in accordance with justice.\n\nThese few points are sufficient to understand the context of the discourse. The other aspects within this example have been explained in their proper places, and a specific aspect will be explained in the subsequent verse."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 22,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 22\n\nBenefit is Achieved in Accordance with Capability and Receptivity\n\nIn this interrogative sentence as well, the predicate (khabar) is omitted. We have explained it in the translation.\n\nThis is said to console the Prophet (pbuh)—showing that benefit is always achieved in accordance with capability and receptivity. The rain of God's mercy falls upon both wet and dry, but every land does not benefit from it identically; the land which possesses capability flourishes with it, but the barren land remains desolate. In the same way, the rain which has fallen in the form of the Qur'an will not benefit everyone identically; rather, those who have kept alive their natural capabilities, Allah will open their chests for Islam through it. As for those who have lost their natural capabilities to make their hearts like stone, they will remain deprived of its benefit, and for such hard-hearted ones, who remained like stone even after the reminder of Allah, is only destruction. Such people are in clear deviation, because they have lost their way not in the darkness of the night, but in the full light of day, despite God's guidance. In this interrogative sentence as well, the predicate is omitted, which we have opened in the translation.\n\n'from the remembrance of Allah' (min dhikri-llah) is used here in the sense of: 'from Allah's reminding them'."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 23,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 23\n\nThe Attribute of the Qur'an and Its Influence\n\n'a consistent Book' (Kitaban mutashabihan) is an attribute of the Qur'an, because its every part is consistent, harmonious, and of the same color; from wherever you open and read it, all its basic teachings will be refreshed in your mind. The color and style of its every group, and indeed of its every Surah, are different. The core themes (amood) are also different, but alongside this difference, there is such an all-encompassing unity in it that from wherever you look at it, the primary beauty of the Qur'an appears before your eyes. By looking at the commentary we have presented of the different groups of the Surahs, our claim can be verified. The Qur'an's being sent down in this form possesses a great benefit in terms of teaching. In this way, the reader is made to observe from different angles all those realities to which the Qur'an invites.\n\nThe analysis of 'Masani' (pairs) has passed under verse 87 of Surah Al-Hijr. This points to the fact that the Surahs of the Qur'an have been made in pairs. Those who have interpreted its meaning as 'things repeated' have held a view contrary to the lexicon and the parallels of the Qur'an. The value which the pairing of the Surahs possesses in terms of teaching has been explained in the introduction and also under the aforementioned verse of Surah Al-Hijr.\n\nThe word 'julood' (skins) in this verse is used in the sense of the body's hair and also in the sense of the entire body; in the Arabic language, they mention the whole and mean the part, and also mention the part and mean the whole.\n\n'Taleenu' (relax/soften) here encompasses the meaning of turning; because of this, it is followed by the preposition 'ila' (to/toward).\n\nHaving understood the words and styles, reflect on the theme of the verse.\n\nIt states: We have sent down in the form of this Qur'an the best of discourse, whose every part is consistent and of the same color, and We have made all its Surahs in pairs so that its every word is well impressed upon the reader's mind. From whichever angle they look at it, the actual reality is not hidden from their eyes. It should be kept in mind here that the state of the Torah is entirely different from the Qur'an. The state of the Qur'an is: if after Al-Baqarah, you read Al-Imran, though there is a great difference between their core themes, addressees, reasoning, and styles, in Al-Imran as well, all those realities appear before the eyes anew which passed in Al-Baqarah. On the contrary, the state of the Torah is: if after Genesis, you read Exodus, Leviticus, or Numbers, you become entirely disconnected from the previous books. The Jews' forgetting and distorting of the Torah was also largely due to this disconnectedness of its various parts.\n\n'whereat shiver the skins of those who fear their Lord'—meaning the influence of the Qur'an is such that those who fear God feel a shiver in their bodies on hearing its reminding. If someone is not influenced by it, it means their heart is entirely empty of God's light and has become hard like stone.\n\n'then their skins and their hearts relax at the remembrance of Allah'—meaning this Qur'an produces a tenderness in hearts, by whose effect their bodies and their hearts both soften to turn to the remembrance of Allah. The softening of hearts is obvious; the softening of bodies means that no trace of pride and arrogance remains within them... if a person has pride and arrogance, their neck remains tense and their body stiff, and they walk stamping their feet on the earth. On the contrary, those who fear God possess lowliness and humility, whose effect is prominent from their walk and every posture of their body.\n\n'That is the guidance of Allah by which He guides whom He wills.' 'That' (dhalika) points to the Qur'an—meaning this Qur'an is the guidance sent down by Allah by which He guides whomever He pleases. This means He has appointed a specific Sunnah for this guidance. According to this Sunnah, those who are deserving of guidance receive guidance from it, and those who are not deserving remain deprived of it. We have been explaining this Sunnah in various places in this book.\n\n'And He whom Allah leaves astray - for him there is no guide'—meaning according to this Sunnah of Allah, no one can guide the one who has deserved deviation. Within this is consolation for the Prophet (pbuh)—stating that there is no need to grieve over such people."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 24,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 24\n\nThe Helplessness of the Arrogant on the Day of Judgment\n\nIn this interrogative sentence as well, the predicate (khabar) is omitted. We have explained it in the translation.\n\nThis is a depiction of the helplessness of those arrogant people—showing that the reward and punishment which they denied with great arrogance in this world, a Day is about to come when its result will overcome them in such a terrifying form that they will try to use their faces as shields to protect themselves from it. A person's most beloved and honorable part is their face. They try first of all to protect it from every calamity and do not want to let any harm reach it. But the state of the punishment of the Hereafter will be such that on that Day, the arrogant will possess nothing which they can use as a shield; therefore, they will be forced to put their very faces before it, which they carried with such arrogance before those who warned them of it.\n\n'And it will be said to the wrongdoers, \"Taste what you used to earn!\"' 'Wrongdoers' (Zalimun) refers to these very arrogant people, because they became wrongdoers to their own souls by denying the Qur'an. It states that observing their helplessness, Allah Almighty will show no mercy to them, but they will be told: 'This is what has appeared before you, which is your own earning; so now taste its flavor.'"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 25,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 25-26\n\nWarning to the Quraysh\n\nThis is a warning to the Quraysh—stating that they should not mock the punishment of which they are being warned. Today conditions are favorable; because of this, they do not understand from where the punishment can appear. The nations who passed before them similarly fell into pride and denied their messengers. Ultimately, the punishment came upon them from where they had no doubt or assumption.\n\n'So Allah made them taste disgrace in worldly life': This punishment of disgrace came upon those nations because they showed arrogance against Allah's messengers and denied the truth despite the complete establishment of proof. We have repeatedly referred to this Sunnah of Allah regarding the messengers—showing that once the nation is determined on denying the messenger, Allah Almighty necessarily destroys them after the expiry of the period of the establishment of proof. Following this punishment of the world, they will also have to face the punishment of the Hereafter, and that is a highly severe thing."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 26,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 27,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 27-28\n\nA Specific Attribute of the Qur'an\n\n'Daraba mathalan' (presenting an example) means presenting the words of wisdom and advice in the style of parables. This style of parables is highly effective for teaching and explaining realities, particularly those realities which relate to an unseen world. For this reason, the Prophets (peace be upon them) employ this attribute of speech extensively. The Torah, the Gospel, and the Psalms are all filled with parables, and Hazrat Sulaiman's (peace be upon him) book of wisdom is named 'Parables' (Proverbs). Because of this characteristic, this phrase began to be used also in the sense of expressing a wise word, whether in the form of a parable or in a general style. Its analysis has passed in its proper place.\n\n'an Arabic Qur'an, without any deviance': This describes that attribute of the Qur'an which specifically concerns the Arabs—showing that Allah Almighty has sent it down in Arabic, and has placed no deviance or complexity in it, but has explained all those matters in a highly eloquent language and a simple and heart-touching style which are essential for success in this world and the Hereafter. If people do not value it, they have disregarded the greatest favor of Allah and His greatest honor, and if they fall under the grasp of His punishment after this establishment of proof, they deserve it.\n\nIn the first verse, it is 'that perhaps they will remember' (la'allahum yatadhakkaroon), and in the second, 'that perhaps they will fear Allah' (la'allahum yattaqoon)—meaning the primary objective of sending down the Qur'an with this care is that those who are asleep in negligence receive reminding, and the final objective is that they avoid the punishment which is the logical consequence of this negligence and indifference, and which will necessarily appear in this world if people remain firm on their stubbornness, and which they must face in the Hereafter."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 28,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 29,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 29\n\nThe Parable of Tawhid and Shirk\n\nThis explains the reality of Tawhid and shirk through a parable—showing that the example of a polytheist is like that of a slave who is simultaneously in the servitude of several different-minded masters, and the example of a monotheist is like that of a slave who is in the servitude of a single master. After this, the question is asked: reflect on whether the state of both slaves will be identical? The meaning is: no slave ever agrees that in place of the servitude of a single master, he has to serve several different-minded and quarreling masters. Human nature is satisfied and agreed upon the servitude of a single God because the need and dependence inherent in it finds no solution without believing in Him. Its proof is present in his heart and also outside of him. As for other partners and deities, once his need is fulfilled by a single God, why would he put the collar of their servitude on his neck! If a person does so, he rebels against his nature, and entangles himself in such a difficulty in which no sensible person would ever agree to be entangled.\n\n'Praise be to Allah' (Al-Hamdulillah)—this is the answer to the question which Allah Himself has given, showing that He alone is the deserving recipient of praise, and all blessings are His gifts, so show gratitude to Him alone and worship and obey Him. When He has not commanded to worship anyone as His partner, why do you put the collar of others' servitude on your necks according to your own assumption!\n\n'But most of them do not know'—meaning this reality is indeed obvious, but the state of the majority of people is that they do not understand this.\n\nThe Psychological Proof for Tawhid\n\nThis is a psychological proof for Tawhid, the complete explanation of which we have made in our treatise *Haqiqat-e-Tawhid*. Man, by his nature, is a highly ambitious creation. He never agrees to the servitude of anyone. He performs the servitude of a One God because His servitude is imbued within his nature, and he finds no peace in his various weaknesses without this support. For the servitude of others, not only is there no demand within him, but a severe aversion exists, provided his nature is not distorted.\n\nIn the verse, the word 'mutashakisoon' (quarreling) also points to an important psychological reality. 'Tashakus' means to differ. 'Shuraka'un mutashakisoon' means: partners who are different-minded and fighting with one another. It should be kept in mind here that the polytheists believe regarding their deities that jealousy and rivalry remain between them, because of which they sometimes collide in such a way that their battle does not end for a long time. Whose ruin has arrived that he would agree to become the slave of many such different-minded deities simultaneously! Human nature cannot tolerate this difficulty and disgrace, but the polytheist tolerates it, which is proof that he is entirely devoid of the consciousness of humanity and the correct sense of his own honor."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 30,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 30-31\n\nConsolation for the Prophet (pbuh) and a Warning for the Opponents\n\nThis is consolation for the Prophet (pbuh) and his companions, and a threat and warning for the opponents—showing that this dispute of Tawhid and shirk which is initiated today must be presented one day in the court of God as well. Addressing the Prophet (pbuh), He stated: 'You are to die, and indeed, these opponents of yours will also die. Then, as two parties of a case, you and they will present yourselves before God's court.' You will be asked: 'What did you deliver and teach them?' They will be asked: 'What did they reply to it?' Then, the actual and final decision will be made there as as to who was upon the truth and who was upon falsehood. The meaning is: there is no need to grieve over the bickering and stubbornness of these people. In this world, Satan has also received respite; because of this, his work is also ongoing, and the requirement of His wisdom was this; but this respite is about to end, and this entire matter will be presented in the court of Allah. On that Day, only those will overcome and be successful who are upon the truth."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 31,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 32,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 32-33\n\nThe Decision of God's Punishment\n\nThe decision that will be made there has been informed beforehand—showing that at that time, who will be more deprived and unjust to themselves than those who fabricated a lie against Allah, and then, when the truth was sent down to correct this lie, denied it. Fabricating a lie against Allah refers to shirk, because the polytheists claim regarding their assumed partners that God has associated them, whereas He has sent down no proof in their favor. 'Truth' (As-Sidq) refers here to the Qur'an, because in every matter, it has removed differences to present the truth.\n\nIn 'when it has come to him' (idh ja'ahu), the restriction is meant to point to the aspect of the establishment of proof—showing that if some truth is hidden and a person remains deprived of it, there may be some excuse for them; but when the truth comes and stands before them, and a stubborn person continuously denies it, it means they are denying the existence of the sun at midday.\n\n'Is there not in Hell a residence for the disbelievers?'—this question asks: is not the residence of such disbelievers destined for Hell! Meaning, whoever possesses any reason will accept that such people must indeed deserve Hell. Consequently, on that Day, such will happen. All such disbelievers will be packed into Hell.\n\n'And the one who has brought the truth and believed in it - those are the righteous.' Before 'believed in it' (saddaqa bihi), 'man' (who/whoever) is omitted, and 'righteous' (Al-Muttaqoon) here is used in the sense of those who remain safe from the punishment and Hell.\n\nThis describes the reward of the second party, i.e., the presenter of the Qur'an and those who believed in it—showing that on that Day, only those will remain safe from Hell who brought the truth, i.e., the Prophet (pbuh), and those who believed in this truth. After 'Saddaq', the preposition 'bi' is an indication that they believed in it with a sincere heart."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 33,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 34,
        "Tafseer": "\"They will have whatever they desire with their Lord. That is the reward of the doers of good -\" (34)\n\nThis describes their reward in highly comprehensive words—stating that they will have whatever they desire with their Lord; no obstacle will remain in the path of their desires and wishes. Allah Almighty will fulfill their every desire. With 'with their Lord' ('inda Rabbihim), it emerged that the highest rank for the servants is the proximity of God, not absorption into His essence, as a group of Sufis has assumed.\n\n'That is the reward of the doers of good' is a warning that this reward is for the doers of good. Every claimant of faith in the Qur'an will not deserve it. Only those will deserve it who fulfill the right of 'Ihsan' (goodness) along with faith."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 35,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 35\n\nThe Objective of the Day of Recompense\n\nThis describes the objective of that Day of Recompense which was mentioned above—showing that Allah Almighty has appointed this Day so that He may remove the worst effects of His good servants' deeds and reward them with the best reward of their deeds. It should be kept in mind here that in this world, a person can neither form a correct estimate of the effects and results of their bad deeds, nor of the value and price of the reward of their good deeds. This world is temporary, and this reward or punishment relates to a world whose punishment is eternal and whose reward is also eternal; for this reason, the words 'worst' (aswa'a) and 'best' (ahsan) are used in the verse. The meaning is: Allah Almighty has appointed this Day of Recompense to save those who adopt the path of faith and deeds from the effects of the worst aspect of their deeds, and to bless them with the blessings of the best aspect of their deeds. Thus, in this, guidance is also given: a person should not look only at the immediate effects and results of their deeds, but at those effects and results which are to be produced in an eternal life."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 36,
        "Tafseer": "6. Subsequent Theme: Verses 36–52\n\nNext, the Prophet (pbuh) is consoled—stating: those who are warning you of their deities, tell them: 'Besides this Lord Who is the Creator of the heavens and the earth, no one can bring any benefit or harm to me; whatever they can do, tell them to do it. You continue with your work without any fear; you are responsible only for your duty, and carry no responsibility for their disbelief or faith. If these people rely on their assumed intercession, clarify its reality to them, and if they are proud of their present worldly successes, tell them of their transience.' Recite the verses.\n\n7. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\nAyah 36-37\n\nAllah's Protection is Sufficient for His Servant\n\nThis is consolation for the Prophet (pbuh)—stating: these polytheists warn you of the wrath and anger of their deities upon your opposing them, claiming that if you do not stop opposing their ancestral religion, they will afflict you with some calamity. 'Is not Allah sufficient for His servant' to protect and sustain him, such that their deities could place him in danger! Whoever believes in Allah, Allah is sufficient for his protection. Without Allah's permission, nothing can bring any harm to him. If someone is in the fear that something can bring harm to him contrary to Allah Almighty's will, they do not consider God sufficient for their protection, and this is indeed disbelief and polytheism.\n\n'And He whom Allah leaves astray - for him there is no guide.' This is a reproach over the ignorance of these polytheists—showing that they are uttering such foolish things because they have been struck by God's punishment due to their bad deeds. These are people who have fallen under the law of God; because of this, Allah has left them astray, and whoever is left astray by God, no one can guide them. This points to that Sunnah of Allah of which we have been clarifying in various places. Its reference is given here for the consolation of the Prophet (pbuh)—stating: do not care about the words of such stubborn people. No one can bring such people to the straight path.\n\n'Is not Allah Exalted in Might and Owner of Retribution?'—meaning if God is not sufficient for His servants, it means He is not Exalted in Might (Al-Aziz), whereas He is Exalted in Might, because He Who is not Exalted in Might cannot be God. At the same time, He is 'Dhu-ntiqaam' (Owner of Retribution)—meaning He is neither going to leave those who usurp His rights, nor forgive those who oppress His servants, but He will take retribution for every single thing. This is asked in an interrogative style because these attributes are entirely self-evident attributes of God. Without them, God cannot be conceived; so when God is Exalted in Might and also the Owner of Retribution, His servants should have full trust in Him that He will protect them from every danger."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 37,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 38,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 38\n\nThe Polytheists' Contradiction of Thought\n\nThat is, these people are caught in a contradiction of thought. On one hand, their state is: if you ask them who created the heavens and the earth, they will reply: 'Allah!' On the other hand, they have taken others besides Allah as partners in His divinity and are warning you of them. As if they assume that God is the Creator, but He is not the Owner and Master of His created world. Ask these simpletons: 'If God intends some harm for me, will your assumed deities save me from it? Similarly, if He intends some favor for me, will your idols of stone and wood hold His hand?' We have discussed under another verse that when 'Afara'aytum' (Have you considered) occurs in this context, it is for contempt and expressing wonder.\n\n'Say, \"Sufficient for me is Allah; upon Him rely those who [sincerely] rely.\"' It states: tell these simpletons: 'Allah is sufficient for me; neither do I fear anyone besides Him, nor do I have hope in anyone besides Him. He alone is the Sustainer of my every need; therefore, I rely on Him, and those who rely, rely on Him alone.' Those who rely on others besides Him have established their hopes on sand."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 39,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 39-40\n\nDeclaration of Disassociation from the Polytheists\n\nAfter 'Innee 'amilun' (Indeed, I am working), the words 'ala makanatee' (in my position) are omitted to avoid repetition.\n\nThis is a declaration of disassociation and self-sufficiency through the tongue of the Prophet (pbuh)—implying: tell them: 'If you are not ready to listen to my word, you work in your position and on your way, and I will continue working on my way. You will soon see upon whom comes a punishment that disgraces him, and upon whom descends a constant punishment!' The meaning is: if you are not going to desist from your way, I am also not going to desist from my invitation. Now, the future will decide who is disgraced and who is honored—who is destroyed forever and who is established by Allah! The mention of 'a disgraceful punishment' (adhabun yukhzeehi) is in view of the opponents' arrogance, and 'a constant punishment' (adhabun muqeem) refers to that punishment which, when it descends upon a nation, remains permanently to uproot it. We have mentioned in another place that two kinds of punishments come upon nations. One is that which comes merely to warn and alert. This kind of punishment comes like a wind to warn and pass. The second is that which completely destroys the nation's existence. The punishment which comes upon a nation after the establishment of proof by the messenger is of this very nature; because of this, the words 'a constant punishment' (adhabun muqeem) are used for it."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 40,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 41,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 41\n\nThe Messenger is Responsible Only for the Establishment of Proof\n\nAfter making the declaration of disassociation, the Prophet (pbuh) is consoled—stating that you have discharged the responsibility which lay upon you, and now there is no need to grieve over them. It states: We have sent down the Book to you for the people in truth—meaning through this Book We have clearly distinguished between truth and falsehood. Now, those who accept it will reform their world and their Hereafter, and those who deny it will only lead themselves into deviation, harming you in no way. Your responsibility was only to invite them to this truth; it was not your responsibility that you must force them to walk upon the path of faith and Islam. You have discharged your duty; now the responsibility is theirs, so leave them to their state."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 42,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 42\n\nAfter 'wa-llatee lam tamut' (and those who did not die), the word 'yatawaffa-ha' (He takes them) is omitted due to contextual clarity. We have opened it in the translation.\n\nReference to Some Signs in Support of the Above Realities\n\nThat is, human life and death are entirely in the control of Allah. He whose appointed term is complete, Allah takes his soul; and he whose death has not arrived, He makes him observe the trial of death and being raised alive after death every day. In the night when he sleeps, this is as if Allah is making him observe death, and in the morning when he stands up, this is making him observe the Resurrection. In this way, every person is being shown every day that he should not consider his life as permanent, but should remember that God has granted him respite for a specified time; his soul is in the hand of God at every moment. He can take it whenever He wills.\n\n'Indeed in that are signs for a people who give thought.' It states that in this, there are many signs for those who reflect.\n\nWithin this, the first sign is that just as creation and management are entirely in the control of Allah, life and death are entirely in His control. Then from this, it emerged that when in the matter of life and death, no one else has any share, how can anyone else become a protector and place of return after death? For this reason, the Being worthy of trust is Allah alone; upon Him alone must those who rely, rely.\n\nThe second sign in this is that being raised alive again after death is not in the least improbable. In this world, the rehearsal of death and being raised after death is occurring before every person every day, provided he possesses eyes to see it. The supplication which a believer recites upon waking up in the morning: 'Praise to Allah Who gave us life after He made us die, and to Him is the Resurrection' is an expression of this very lesson of warning.\n\nThe third sign in this is that this universe, in its very existence, is an excellent training ground for all those realities upon which the reform of human life depends, and to which the Qur'an is inviting."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 43,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 43\n\nWonder over the Polytheists' Foolishness\n\nThis question is by way of wonder and reproach—asking: have these foolish people, despite all these obvious realities, taken intercessors besides Allah—hoping that if God seizes them, they will save them! It states: ask them: 'Even though they do not possess authority over anything, nor have any knowledge or consciousness, will they still hope that they will be their intercessors before God?' The meaning is: as far as authority is concerned, it belongs to no one besides Allah. As for knowledge and consciousness, even in this regard, no one holds such a status as to add anything to Allah Almighty's knowledge. Particularly, these idols upon whose intercession they rely have no reality, let alone possessing any knowledge or consciousness."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 44,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 44\n\nThe Restrictions and Conditions of Intercession\n\nIt states: tell these simpletons that intercession belongs entirely to Allah; no one will dare to intercede before Him without His permission, and after permission, they will intercede only for the one for whom permission has been granted. Then they will say only that which is the truth; no one will have the opportunity to say anything contrary to the truth before God. All these restrictions and conditions of intercession have been described in detail in the Qur'an, and we have been explaining them in their proper places. This same reality is expressed here in comprehensive words: 'intercession belongs entirely to Allah'; those who assume that regardless of their deeds, their deities will save them from God's grasp will see the end of their false hopes on the Day of Judgment.\n\n'To Him belongs the sovereignty of the heavens and the earth. Then to Him you will be returned'—meaning the sovereignty of the heavens and the earth is in the control of God alone, and the presentation of everyone must be before Him. Neither is there any share of anyone in this sovereignty, nor will anyone else be a protector and place of return."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 45,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 45\n\nThe Belief of False Intercession is a Backdoor to Escape from the Account of the Hereafter\n\nThis points to a major cause of the coming into existence of polytheism and intercession—showing that since the Hereafter is the Day of the manifestation of God's perfect justice and reward and punishment, and believing in it places highly heavy responsibilities upon man, those who wish to avoid these responsibilities take the cover of polytheism and intercession. They have neither the courage to fulfill the requirements of faith and deeds, nor are they ready to accept any restriction on the desires of the self; for this reason, first, they do not believe in the Hereafter, and even if they do, they secure themselves, according to their own assumption, from all its dangers by inventing the belief of polytheism and intercession. All their reliance is on the intercession of their assumed intercessors; because of this, if Tawhid is mentioned before them, their hearts feel aversion, because then the Hereafter stands before them with all its terrors. However, when their assumed partners and intercessors are mentioned, they take a breath of relief, because in this case, they receive a license to lead a life free of the Hereafter. This shows that the belief of false intercession is, in reality, a backdoor to escape from the responsibilities of the Hereafter."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 46,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 46\n\nInstruction to the Prophet to Turn away from the Deniers of the Hereafter and to Prepare for it\n\nThis is a supplication instructed to the Prophet (pbuh), from which it emerges that the matter of these people who are not ready to face the reality is now closed. They will live in this and die in this. However, you supplicate: 'O Creator of the heavens and the earth, Knower of the unseen and the witnessed, You will judge between Your servants on the Day of Judgment regarding that over which they differ'—meaning: 'You will necessarily bring a Day in which Your perfect justice will stand manifest.' Since on the manifestation of this perfect justice depends the purposeful nature of this world, and His being a Wise and Just God is proven by its manifestation, this supplication is instructed."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 47,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 47\n\nA Timely Warning to the Polytheists\n\nThat is, these polytheists, in the love of this world, have devised these backdoors to escape from the Hereafter, whereas when they face the severe punishment of the Day of Resurrection, their state will be such that even if they possessed all that is in the earth and the like of it with it, they would offer it as a ransom to escape from this punishment.\n\n'And there will appear to them from Allah that which they had not taken into account.' Man is highly generous in giving allowances to his desires. Then, he observes in this world that he continuously commits the greatest crimes, yet there is no grasp; because of this, he becomes entirely indifferent to the thought of the Hereafter, and if someone draws his attention to it and tries to make him understand the requirements of God's justice and retribution, he considers it merely as the creation of an illusion, assuming: 'even if the Hereafter is to occur, how can Allah Almighty deal with people like us in the manner of which this Qur'an is warning us!' This is a general fitnah in which the majority of people are caught. To warn such people, He stated: when that Day of Account comes, such things will appear from Allah for these dreamers of sweet dreams as they cannot conceive today. Today they are deceived by His generosity, but when they see His justice and retribution, their eyes will open and they will see that God is as Severe in retribution as He is Generous."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 48,
        "Tafseer": "\"And there will appear to them the evils of what they earned, and they will be enveloped by what they used to mock.\" (48)\n\nAnother Timely Warning\n\nSimilarly, the severity of the results of man's bad deeds is also not clear to him in this world. He cannot estimate here in what color the harvest of his bad deed or bad thought will grow, and what kind and how many poisonous fruits it will bear. In the Hereafter, the results of all his thoughts and deeds will appear before him in their actual form, and he will see that the things which he considered contemptible and mocked have now completely enveloped him."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 49,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 49\n\nA Destructive Misconception\n\nThis has been explained under verse 8 of this Surah. This is a strange weakness of man: when some adversity touches him, he supplicates to God, but when Allah Almighty removes his adversity to bless him with His favor, he forgets both God and his adversity and attributes this blessing either to others—claiming: 'this was achieved by the blessing and favor of such and such' (as is mentioned in verse 8), or declares it as the miracle of his own planning, capability, and intelligence (as is pointed out in this verse). Meaning: he declares the source of this blessing to be either others besides God or his own self, and both of these are forms of shirk, because whatever blessing a servant receives is received from God alone, and others have no role in it except as a medium and source. His science and capability are also the gift of Allah; if they become a source of success, they become so through His guidance. 'Rather, it is a trial, but most of them do not know'—meaning no blessing is received from anyone besides God, nor is it the result of his own capability and entitlement; rather, it is received from Allah Almighty, and He tests His servant through it—seeing whether he remains grateful to his Lord or falls into arrogance and rebellion upon receiving it. But the majority of people are unaware of this reality, and this is what entangles them in shirk and corruption. In the story of Qarun in Surah Al-Qasas, this reality has been described in highly clear words:\n\n'Indeed, Qarun was from the people of Moses, but he tyrannized them. And We gave him of treasures whose keys would burden a band of strong men... He said, \"I was only given it because of knowledge I have.\" Did he not know that Allah had destroyed before him of generations those who were greater than him in power and greater in accumulation?' (76-78)."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 50,
        "Tafseer": "\"Those before them had already said it, but they were not availed by what they used to earn.\" (50)\n\nThat is, those before them also said this. This refers to the statement: 'I was only given it because of knowledge'—meaning before these rebels of the Quraysh, there have already passed those who made such claims, among whom was Qarun whose statement passed above. It states: those who fell into this pride, when they were seized in God's grasp, those things which they had achieved through their capability and science were of no use to them. Thus, the example of Qarun is described in the Qur'an—showing that he considered himself a great expert in trade and finance, but God caused his treasures to swallow him along with his treasures, and at that time, none of his planning was of any use to him."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 51,
        "Tafseer": "\"So the evil consequences of what they earned struck them. And those who have wronged of these [people] will be struck by the evil consequences of what they earned; and they will not escape.\" (51)\n\nThat is, those who were caught in this kind of delusion, ultimately the bad results of their deeds came before them. It states: those who have committed this wrong among these people (the Quraysh) will also face the bad results of their bad deeds, and when We seize them, they will not be able to escape from Us."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 52,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 52\n\nProvision and Favor Are in the Control of Allah Almighty\n\nExactly this same theme has passed in verse 37 of Surah Ar-Rum. The only difference is that there the words are 'Do they not see' (Awalam yaraw), and here 'Do they not know' (Awalam ya'lamoo). The meaning is: if a person possesses eyes and utilizes their intellect, there is no room for doubt for him in the matter that provision and favor are not related to human capability and choice, but entirely to the will and wisdom of Allah Almighty. He extends it for whomever He pleases and restricts it for whomever He pleases. How many are there who are born with a silver spoon in their mouth in this world without any effort, and how many are there who dedicate their day and night to the thought of the world and also possess the knowledge of earning, yet receive only what Allah has written in their destiny. This observation also occurs in this world daily: a person is a millionaire, billionaire, or even a king today, and the next day he is completely bankrupt or locked in a prison cell. Despite these open observations, if a person is caught in the pride of his wealth: 'I was only given it because of knowledge', it must be accepted that there is some defect in his intellect.\n\n'Indeed in that are signs for a people who believe'—meaning for those who believe, there are many signs in this system of provision and favor. For example:\n\n* That the sovereignty of this universe is in the control of God alone; He bestows upon whomever He pleases and snatches from whomever He pleases, and no one else has any share in it; therefore, reliance must be on Allah Almighty alone.\n\n* That every action of Allah Almighty is under His mercy and wisdom. If He gives more to someone in this world, there is wisdom in it. If He gives less, there is wisdom in it. He tests the gratitude of one by giving more, and the patience of the other by giving less; and this decision of who succeeded and who failed will be made on the Day of Judgment.\n\n* That this world is a home of trial, not of reward; everyone is being tested in it, and for the manifestation of the results of this test, the coming of the Resurrection is inevitable.\n\nIn 'for a people who believe' (li-qawmin yu'minoon), the verb 'believe' is used in the sense of intending to believe. This is a reality: the deviation which man faces in this world is not because realities are hidden, but mostly because realities are obvious but man does not intend to accept them. This has various causes, the details of which have passed in their proper places."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 53,
        "Tafseer": "8. Subsequent Theme: Verses 53–75\n\nNext, the polytheists are invited: 'The backdoors of polytheism and intercession which you have devised out of despair and bad thoughts of God will not open the way to your salvation, but will only increase your ruin. The way of success is to turn to your Lord with a sincere heart and follow this best Book which Allah has sent down for your guidance; otherwise, remember that the time is soon coming when you will beat your heads over your foolishness, but at that time your regret will be of no use.' Recite the verses.\n\n9. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\nAyah 53\n\nRemoving a Major Misconception of the Polytheists\n\nAmong the factors of polytheism, a major factor is also despair or bad thoughts of God. This despair has various aspects, which have been explained in their proper places. Among them is also: the polytheist has no trust in the mercy and forgiveness of God; because of this, he carves some assumed close ones of God according to his own imagination, and by worshipping them, hopes that they will intercede for his forgiveness with God. Those who are caught in this doubt were given this message by Allah Almighty through the Prophet (pbuh)—stating: tell them: 'O My servants who have transgressed against themselves by committing sin or polytheism! Do not despair of the mercy of God to seek the support of others, and seek forgiveness from Him alone. Allah is highly Forgiving and Merciful. He forgives every kind of sin of those of His servants who turn to Him with sincerity.'\n\nThe tone of this verse is proof that the addressees are those who are in the misconception: neither is everyone capable of access to God, nor does He consider everyone's word worthy of attention; under this misconception, they take the support of other means and mediums, whereas such a thought of God is equivalent to despair and bad thoughts of Him, which is not permissible in any case."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 54,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 54\n\nThe Correct Path for the Seekers of Allah's Mercy\n\nThis guides to the correct path which those who seek Allah's mercy and forgiveness must adopt.\n\nIt states: cut yourselves off from other assumed mediums and means to turn to your Lord, repent of your sins to seek His mercy and forgiveness, and before the manifestation of God's punishment, submit yourselves entirely to your Lord. That is: worship and obey Him alone, without associating any partner.\n\n'before there comes to you the punishment' can refer to the punishment of the Hereafter, but here the context is proof that it points to that punishment which necessarily comes upon the deniers after the establishment of proof by the messenger. After the manifestation of this punishment, neither is there any room for anyone to believe, nor are such people helped by anyone. The meaning is: do not be seekers of this punishment; rather, if you desire your own good, think of repentance and reform before it."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 55,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 55\n\nThe Aspects of the Establishment of Proof in the Qur'an\n\nThis explains the preceding theme—stating: the correct path for you is to follow the best of what was revealed to you from your Lord. The best refers, obviously, to the Holy Qur'an, whose being the 'best of statement' (Ahsan-al-Hadeeth) was mentioned in verse 23. The excellence which the Qur'an enjoys over other heavenly scriptures has been explained in various places in this book. For example:\n\n* The Qur'an is the final and perfect Book of God.\n\n* It is protected from every trace of distortion.\n\n* It is the inviter to the natural religion; because of this, it is free from the severities of previous Shariahs.\n\n* Particularly from the perspective of the Arabs, some of its aspects are worth keeping in view:\n\n  * It is in highly eloquent Arabic, presenting a parallel of which others are unable, and this is a great favor of Allah Almighty upon the Arabs that He sent down His final Book in Arabic.\n\n  * This Book has been sent down in the form of pairs (mutashabihan wa masani), which makes its benefit many times greater compared to other scriptures (its explanation has passed above).\n\n  * It invites to the way (Millah) of the Arabs' ancestor, Hazrat Ibrahim (peace be upon him); because of this, its invitation is a familiar thing for the Arabs.\n\nIt states: all these virtues require that you accept this Book immediately and cherish it. If you do not value it, remember that in case of its denial, a punishment will come upon you in such a way that you will have no assumption of it."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 56,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 56\n\nBefore 'an' (lest), a prefixed noun (mudaf) is omitted here, and examples of this have passed. The meaning is: Allah has made all this arrangement so that the time of reckoning does not arrive and those who are negligent have to regret: 'We have shown great negligence regarding God by remaining lost in worldly self-forgetfulness and forgetting the Day of the Hereafter, and committed an additional injustice by continuously mocking those who reminded us of it!'"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 57,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 58,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 58\n\nOr present this excuse: 'If Allah had guided us, we would have been among those who fear Him.' The meaning is: to block such excuses, Allah has sent down His guidance. Now, those who turn away from it carry the entire responsibility for their deviation."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 59,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 59\n\nThis is the reply to the excuse mentioned in verse 57—stating: on that Day, those who present this excuse will be given this reply: 'Allah Almighty did send His verses for your guidance, but you denied them, showed arrogance, and were among the disbelievers.' The meaning is: Allah's way of guidance is not to force it into people's hearts, but He arranges to inform people of His teachings, and leaves it to them to accept or reject. This work was done by Allah, but you did not value it due to your arrogance."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 60,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 60\n\nThe Fate of the Polytheists\n\n'Those who lied about Allah' (kadhaboo 'ala-llah) refers to shirk. Its analysis has passed in its proper place. The meaning is: those who fabricated lies against Allah—claiming that He has associated such and such as His partners, and when they were warned by Allah that He has no partner, they persisted on their view without any proof, merely out of pride; on the Day of Judgment, their faces will be blackened as a retribution for this pride of theirs.\n\n'Is there not in Hell a residence for the arrogant?'—this question asks: is not the residence of such arrogant ones destined for Hell? The meaning is: the deserving of Hell of such self-willed ones is such an obvious thing in which there is no room for difference for anyone. Consequently, all these arrogant ones will be packed into Hell."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 61,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 61\n\nThe Reward of those Who Fear Allah\n\nIn contrast to the arrogant, this describes the reward of those who feared Allah. It states: Allah will give refuge to His servants who are free from pride in their place of safety. 'Bi-mafazatihini'—'bi' is for space, and 'mafazah' means a place of safety and success, which refers to Paradise. That is, on that Day of terror, these people will be delivered to such places where neither will any trouble reach them, nor will they grieve. They will be entirely safe from all regrets of the past and all fears of the future."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 62,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 62-63\n\nSummary of the Discussion\n\nThis places the summary of the entire discussion before us: Allah alone is the Creator of everything, and He is not sitting aside after creating His world, but He alone is the Guardian over everything; therefore, the servants must rely on Him alone. The keys to all the depositories of the heavens and the earth are with Him. Whatever the servants receive from the heavens and the earth, they receive through His favor, and whatever they receive in the Hereafter, they will receive through His favor. Those who denied the verses of Allah and persisted on their shirk are indeed the losers. The ruin of this foolishness of theirs will fall upon them alone, not upon anyone else."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 63,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 64,
        "Tafseer": "10. Subsequent Theme: Verses 64–75\n\nNext are the concluding verses of the Surah. The Surah ends on the same theme with which it began, and we have pointed out in various Surahs this characteristic of the style of the Qur'an—that the theme with which the Surah began is also that on which it ends.\n\nFirst, a declaration is made through the tongue of the Prophet (pbuh)—implying: 'O foolish ones! After these obvious realities, do you command me to worship others besides Allah?' Whereas Allah has revealed to all prophets the very same revelation: 'Whoever associates partners with Allah, all his deeds will perish.' After this, the reality is clarified: these ignorant people have not valued the majesty of God at all, as they have associated such things in His divinity as have no reality, and are carefree regarding the Hereafter relying on them. The majesty of God is such that He will fold the entire earth and heavens in His hand on that Day, and when the Horn is blown once, everyone in the heavens and the earth will fall dead, and when it is blown the second time, all will stand up and the earth will shine with the light of God. At that time, the register of deeds will be opened, the prophets and witnesses will be called, and decisions will be made between people with complete justice. After this, the details of the states of the people of Paradise and the people of Hell are narrated so that those who are dreaming sweet dreams relying on their partners and intercessors are warned... Recite the verses in this light.\n\n11. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\n'Say, \"Is it other than Allah that you order me to worship, O ignorant ones?\"' (64)\n\nA Question by Way of Declaration of Disassociation\n\n'Jahil' (ignorant) is one who follows emotions and desires instead of knowledge and intellect. It states: ask these ignorant ones: 'When all proofs and testimonies are in favor of the fact that the Creator of everything is Allah, and in His hand are the keys of all the heavens and the earth, will you still persist on this—that I worship other things besides Allah?' Above, it has been mentioned that the polytheists warned the Prophet (pbuh) of their deities—stating that if you do not stop opposing the ancestral religion, you will fall under their wrath. Pointing to this, this question was asked by way of a declaration of disassociation—implying: after these obvious realities of nature, will you still demand of me that I become a worshipper of your idols?"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 65,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 65-66\n\nPolytheism Destroys All Deeds\n\nThis is the reply to those people, and since their statement was entirely the statement of the ignorant, He did not address them, but addressed His Prophet to let them hear—stating: 'These ignorant people are demanding polytheism of you, whereas to you and to the messengers before you, this revelation has been made: \"If you associate partners, your deeds will perish, and you will be among the losers.\"' The correct path is only: worship Allah alone, and be of His grateful servants.\n\n'Deeds will perish' (layahbatan-na 'amaluka) means that those deeds which are performed for Allah along with polytheism will also go to waste and remain of no use. Allah Almighty does not accept any deed of a polytheist. He accepts only those virtues of His servants who do not associate anyone with Him.\n\n'Rather, Allah [alone] worship and be among the grateful' points to the reality that the right of gratitude to Allah Almighty which is obligatory upon His every servant is fulfilled only when the servant worships Allah alone. If, in this worship, he associates any partner, he does not remain His grateful servant, but becomes ungrateful, and the entire foundation of his religion collapses."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 66,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 67,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 67\n\nIgnorance of the Majesty of God\n\nThat is, these ignorant people have associated their assumed partners as equals of God because they have not valued His majesty and His grandeur at all. They have measured God with their limited scales; because of this, they could not distinguish between a grain of dust and the sun, or a drop of water and the ocean. Whereas the actual reality is: on the Day of Judgment, this entire earth will be in His grip like a handful of dust, and all the heavens will be folded in His right hand. What compatibility do their deities have with such a Great Being, such that they could become partners in His universe and He would stand in need of their help! 'Qabdah' refers to that much thing which is held in a single grip.\n\n'Exalted is He and high above what they associate with Him'—meaning the Great Essence of Allah is pure and high above all those relationships which these ignorant people attribute to Him. These relationships are contrary to His purity and sanctity, and also contrary to His greatness and majesty."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 68,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 68\n\nThe Helplessness of the Day of Judgment\n\nThis is a further extension of the preceding theme—showing that the polytheists are in the assumption regarding their deities: they enjoy great proximity with Allah, they will do this for their worshippers, and if God seizes them, they will save them through their power and influence; whereas on the Day of Judgment, the state of the entire divinity will be: when the Horn is blown the first time, everyone will fall dead. Only those will remain safe from it whom Allah Almighty wills to keep safe, then when it is blown the second time, all will stand up and stare in wonder... the meaning is: on the Day whose terror is such, who has the audacity to step forward with confidence and intercede for anyone before God? and the God Whose greatness is such that by His single blowing of the Horn the entire creation falls dead and then by His second blowing the entire creation stands alive, who can be His equal!\n\nFrom the exception 'except whom Allah wills' (illa man sha'a-llah), it emerges that some people will remain safe from this general death. Who will these people be? It is difficult to give a decisive answer. However, from verse 75 below, the indication emerges that those angels who surround the Throne of God, exalting Him, will remain safe from it. This is merely an indication; I do not possess certainty on it. I will draw attention to some of its contexts when translating the verse."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 69,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 69\n\nThe New Earth of New Laws and Ordeals\n\n'Al-Ard' (the earth) refers here to that earth which will appear on the Day of Judgment with new laws and rules. In the verse: 'The Day the earth will be replaced with another earth...' (Ibrahim: 48), this is mentioned. Our present earth is illuminated by the light of the sun; because of this, our observation in it is limited only to physical and visible things, but that earth will be illuminated by the light of God; because of this, all meanings and realities will also stand revealed before the people. The true reality of this light is not clarified here. The reason is that our language is incapable of expressing its quantity and quality. But its effects have been pointed out in various places in the Qur'an. For example, in Surah Qaf:\n\n'You were heedless of this; so We have removed from you your cover, and your sight, this Day, is sharp.' (22).\n\nThis shows that today, those realities of whose observation people are incapable, on that earth, all veils will be removed for their observation as well. Similarly, in another place:\n\n'And the earth discharges its burdens, And man says, \"What is [wrong] with it?\" - That Day, it will report its news, Because your Lord has commanded [i.e., inspired] it.' (Al-Zalzalah: 2-5).\n\nAlthough these realities are not hidden from the eyes of the wise today, those whose eyes are veiled cannot see them, but on that Day, by the light of Allah Almighty, they will shine in such a way that those who are blind and deaf to them today will also see and hear them.\n\n'and the record [of deeds] will be placed, and the prophets and the witnesses will be brought, and it will be judged between them in truth, and they will not be wronged'—this points to the effects of the manifestation of the light of the Lord: the reward and punishment of which people are being warned, but which they do not understand today, on that Day, the veil will be removed from this reality, the register of deeds will be placed before them, which is proof that it is the record of people's deeds. The presentation of the prophets and witnesses is described in detail in other places in the Qur'an—showing that Allah Almighty will make the prophets (peace be upon them) testify against their nations as to what they taught and what they replied to it. In Surah Al-Ma'idah, its detail has passed. The word 'shuhada' (witnesses) has vastness and generality. That is, those who are in a position to testify will be called, whether they be of humans or of the angels. Since this Ummah holds the position of 'witnesses of Allah in the earth', its reformers and truthful ones will also be called and asked what they taught and what people replied to it. After this trial, testimony, and presentation, decisions will be made between people with complete justice, and no one will be wronged in the least."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 70,
        "Tafseer": "\"And every soul will be fully compensated for what it did; and He is most knowing of what they do.\" (70)\n\nThis explains 'and they will not be wronged'—showing that everyone will be given exactly what they did, and will be given in full. No increase or decrease will be made in it; for this reason, no question of injustice arises. Everyone will harvest the crop they sowed, and taste the fruit of the tree they planted. 'and He is most knowing of what they do'—and there is also no possibility that God forgets anyone's deed. He is fully aware of what people are doing, and everything is recorded in His clear register.\n\nThe objective of all this detail is to open the eyes of the polytheists—showing them what hopes they harbor, and what the actual reality is which everyone must face."
