    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 71,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 71\n\n'Those who disbelieved' (alladhina kafaroo) refers to these polytheists who have been mentioned from above. Polytheism, as we have explained in its proper place, is disbelief. For this reason, believing in God is credible only when it is with pure Tawhid; if it is mixed with polytheism, it falls under the category of disbelief.\n\nThe Fate of the Disbelievers after the Trial\n\nFollowing the trial and testimony mentioned above, this describes its consequence—stating that after it, those who disbelieved will be driven to Hell in groups. When they reach it, its gates will be opened for them. In another place, it is clarified that it has seven gates, and those who enter will be divided into different parts in accordance with the nature of their crimes.\n\n'And its keepers will say to them...'—observing these unfortunate ones, the keepers of Hell will reproach them: 'O unfortunate ones! Did there not come to you messengers from among yourselves to warn you of this Day, such that you have brought this ruin!' They will admit their crime—stating: 'Indeed, messengers did come, but due to our misfortune, the word of punishment which was decreed against the disbelievers came into effect.' 'The word of punishment' (Kalimat-al-Adhab) refers, as has been explained, to that decisive decree of Allah which He uttered in reply to Iblis's challenge—stating: 'I will fill Hell with you and those who follow you.' Here, only the reference to Allah's decree is made. In other places, there is also the detail that they will admit their crime in highly explicit terms. In Surah Al-Mulk, it is:\n\n'Every time a company is thrown into it, its keepers ask them, \"Did there not come to you a warner?\" They will say, \"Yes, a warner had come to us, but we denied and said, 'Allah has not sent down anything. You are not but in great error.'\" And they will say, \"If only we had been listening or reasoning, we would not be among the companions of the Blaze.\" And they will admit their sin, so [it is] alienation for the companions of the Blaze.' (8-11)."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 72,
        "Tafseer": "\"[To them] it will be said, 'Enter the gates of Hell to abide eternally therein, and wretched is the residence of the arrogant.'\" (72)\n\nFollowing this reply of theirs, they will be told: 'Now enter the gates of Hell, and this entry is eternal.'\n\n'and wretched is the residence of the arrogant'—the arrogant refers, obviously, to those very people who have been mentioned from above. This attribute sheds light on the actual cause of their denial—showing that they turned away from the truth purely out of arrogance and became deserving of that residence which is specified for the arrogant."
