    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 73,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 73\n\nThe Fate of the Righteous\n\n'Sawq' (to drive) is used in the sense of driving something toward somewhere. It can be used in both good and bad contexts. When favorable winds drive the rain clouds toward green fields, this word is used; and when the people of Hell are driven to Hell, it is used in the preceding verse; in this verse, it is used in a good sense. This is because their protectors, the angels, will be before them, behind them, and on their right and left, to lead them under their guidance and protection toward Paradise.\n\nIn this verse, the apodosis (jawab) of 'Idha' (when) is omitted. Its parallel has passed in verses 103-105 of Surah As-Saffat. We have discussed there its context and its eloquence. Sometimes, the nature of the apodosis is such that words are incapable of expressing it. In such places, it is omitted, so that:\n\n'Silence has a meaning which cannot be expressed in words.'\n\n'Tibtum' is among the words of welcome, just as we say: 'be happy, shand and abad, prosper!'\n\n'Those who feared their Lord' (Alladhina-ttaqaw) is used in contrast to 'those who disbelieved' (alladhina kafaroo) to point to the reality: they possessed fear of God; because of this, they did not fall into arrogance, but listened to and accepted the word of Allah's messenger. It states: these people will be led to Paradise in the company of the angels, until, when its gates are opened and its keepers welcome them with peace and greeting... then what they will receive, who can estimate today! 'And no soul knows what has been hidden for them of comfort for eyes' (As-Sajdah: 17)."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 74,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 74\n\nThe Inheritance of Paradise\n\n'Al-Ard' (the land) refers here to that land of Paradise which was mentioned in verse 69. In this verse, its being the land of Paradise is clarified. When the people of Paradise observe that the promises Allah had made through His prophets have been fulfilled step by step, the word of gratitude will flow spontaneously from their tongues: 'Praise to Allah Who has fulfilled His promise to us and made us inherit the land of Paradise, we settle in it wherever we please.' Within 'made us inherit' is a subtle allusion to the reality: this Paradise was given to our father Adam, but Satan deceived him to deprive him of it, and to achieve it again, Allah Almighty had appointed this condition: the progeny of Adam must go to the world to fight with Satan; so those who defeat Satan will inherit this Paradise, and those who fall into his traps will enter Hell along with him. The meaning is: this is the favor of Allah that we achieved success in this test and achieved again our father's lost Paradise.\n\n'so we settle in Paradise wherever we will'—just as regarding the people of Paradise, it has passed that they will have whatever they desire, similarly, this is said regarding them: they will settle in Paradise wherever they please with full authority. This shows that there will be nothing to obstruct their desires and wishes. This is a station of which no concept can be formed in this world. Its reality will be understood only when that new world appears with new laws, and man appears with his new powers and capabilities, and this earth shines with the light of its Lord.\n\n'excellent is the reward of the [righteous] workers' stands in contrast to 'wretched is the residence of the arrogant'. In this contrast, the requirement was that 'those who show humility' (khashi'een) or 'those who fear' (muttaqeen) or a similar word occurred, but this would only fulfill the right of contrast, without making any specific addition to the meaning; by the word 'workers' (Al-Amileen), the addition is made to the meaning: for the achievement of Paradise, the actual thing is work, and those who are dreaming of Paradise relying on false intercessions are living in a fool's paradise."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 39,
        "AyahNumber": 75,
        "Tafseer": "Ayah 75\n\nThe State of the Angels on the Day of Judgment\n\nThe context is proof that this verse is connected with verse 69: 'And the earth will shine with the light of its Lord...' above, and 'the angels' refers to the bearers of the Throne and those of their category, as is prominent from 'surrounding the Throne' (haffeena min hawli-l-arsh). Their mention has occurred in the subsequent Surah—Surah Ghafir—in these words:\n\n'Those [angels] who carry the Throne and those around it exalt [Allah] with praise of their Lord and believe in Him and ask forgiveness for those who have believed, [saying], \"Our Lord, You have encompassed all things in mercy and knowledge, so forgive those who have repented and followed Your way and protect them from the punishment of Hellfire.\"' (7).\n\nOn that Day of testimony and justice, the state of the angels will be this—showing that the polytheists, whose entire reliance is on the angels' intercession, should understand: on that Day of terror, they too will be in fear, surrounding the Throne to perform the glorification of their Lord. It should be kept in mind that this is the state of those angels who are the bearers of the Throne. Then what will be the state of those general angels who do not hold this rank? The meaning is: on that Day, even the greatest angels will be concerned only with themselves, so how can they intercede for others!\n\n'and it will be judged between them in truth'—meaning decisions will be made between people in accordance with truth and justice; neither will any intercession occur, nor will anyone dare to do so.\n\n'and it will be said, \"Praise to Allah, Lord of the worlds\"'—meaning after the manifestation of this perfect justice and mercy, from every corner will rise this voice: 'Praise to Allah, Lord of the worlds!' That is, the believers will raise this voice, and the angels surrounding the Throne will also join in harmony with them.\n\nFrom this verse, it is learned that what makes Allah Almighty worthy of praise and gratitude is His justice and His distinction between the righteous and the wicked. If this had been absent, this world would be reduced to a place of lawlessness, and no one would accept the Creator of such a place as worthy of praise. On the Day of Judgment, when His perfect justice and His perfect mercy stand manifest, every doubt of everyone will be removed, and from every corner will rise the song of His praise. It is as if the morning of praise of which people were waiting has risen, and this world has shone with the light of God!\n\nBy the grace of Allah, the commentary of this Surah is completed on these lines. Praise be to Allah, Lord of the worlds.\n\nRahman Abad\n24 June, 1975 AD."
